SIMPLE: pupa
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pupa
<hw>Pu"pa</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> L.
<plw>Pup⟦ae⟧</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, E. <plw>Pupas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L. <ets>pupa</ets> girl. doll, puppet, fem. of <ets>pupus</ets>.
Cf. <er>Puppet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any
insect in that stage of its metamorphosis which usually immediately
precedes the adult, or imago, stage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Among insects belonging to the higher orders, as the
Hymenoptera, Diptera, Lepidoptera, the pupa is inactive and takes no
food; in the lower orders it is active and takes food, and differs
little from the imago except in the rudimentary state of the sexual
organs, and of the wings in those that have wings when adult. The term
<xex>pupa</xex> is sometimes applied to other invertebrates in analogous
stages of development.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A genus of air-breathing land
snails having an elongated spiral shell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Coarctate pupa</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Obtected pupa</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a pupa which is incased in
the dried-up skin of the larva, as in many Diptera.</cd> --
<col><b>Masked pupa</b></col>, <cd>a pupa whose limbs are bound down and
partly concealed by a chitinous covering, as in
Lepidoptera.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pupal</ent>⟦br⟧
